This collection combines serials relating to the law drawn from two discrete groups of material held by the Tamiment Library. The first was a partially inventoried backlog of serials, received by the library through donations, subscriptions, and in archival collections. The second group consisted of around 1,700 serials, newspapers, and magazines, organized by title as an artificial collection, referred to as Periodicals.001 or Boxed Newspapers. This material was combined, inventoried, and arranged and described in subject-based categories in 2017. The accession number related to this collection is 2017.049.

The Tamiment Library and Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives Collection of Law Serials contains over 180 titles on legal issues in the United States (US), Europe, and Central America between 1935 and 2013.  The bulk of the collection consists of American serials published between the 1960s and the 1980s.  A large number of the serials consist of publications of the National Lawyers Guild, both the national organization and state chapters, and Amnesty International.  Topics include the work of lawyers and judges, reform of the American legal system, and legal rights of American citizens.  The collection contains serials published by organizations focused on specific issues, including welfare, prison reform, legal defense for specific individuals, consumer rights, and hate crimes.  Large runs of titles include Amnesty International's <emph render='italic'>Matchbox</emph> and <emph render='italic'>Amnesty Action</emph>, the Bay Area regional office of the National Lawyers Guild's <emph render='italic'>Conspiracy</emph>, and the New York office of the National Lawyers Guild's <emph render='italic'>Blind Justice</emph>.
